Special case .NET assemblies (?)

Small example:
---
nasm
; hello.asm - 64-bit Windows Hello World (NASM)
extern MessageBoxA
extern ExitProcess

section .data
    caption db 'Assembly Example', 0
    message db 'Hello, this is a small source code!', 0

section .text
    global main
main:
    ; Register-based calling convention for x64 Windows (Shadow Space)
    sub rsp, 28h          ; Reserve 40 bytes of shadow space on stack
    
    mov rcx, 0            ; HWND hWnd = NULL
    mov rdx, message      ; LPCSTR lpText
    mov r8, caption       ; LPCSTR lpCaption
    mov r9, 0             ; UINT uType = MB_OK
    call MessageBoxA      ; Call the Windows API
    
    mov rcx, 0            ; UINT uExitCode = 0
    call ExitProcess      ; Exit the program
---
To turn this into a program we need an assembler and a linker
First assembler
nasm -f win64 hello.asm -o hello.obj
Second link
link hello.obj /subsystem:windows /entry:main user32.lib kernel32.lib /out:hello.exe

Let move deeper into the code it self.
The register:
General purpose registers: in the CPU, each core can have its own general purpose registers, which is it own storage space which is extremely fast. When doing certain task, the cpu will try to put data in there
instead of memory because it a lot faster for cpu to access data in register when compare to memory. If the data is too large to fit in a register, a register will hold a pointer to the data so it can be accessed.


There are 8 main general purpose registers

RAX - Known as the accumulator register. Often used to store the return value of a function.
RBX - Sometimes known as the base register, not to be confused with the base pointer. Sometimes used as a base pointer for memory access.
RDX - Sometimes known as the data register.
RCX - Sometimes known as the counter register. Used as a loop counter.
RSI - Known as the source index. Used as the source pointer in string operations.
RDI - Known as the destination index. Used as the destination pointer in string operations.
RSP - The stack pointer. Holds the address of the top of the stack.
RBP - The base pointer. Holds the address of the base (bottom) of the stack.

Moreover, each register doesn't have to hold these type of data, but it gonna be extremely helpful when us and computer follow the rule to know where is value of a function went.
There are additional registers r8 to r15 which are designed to be used by integer type values and don't have any special uses
